481
00:29:08.072 --> 00:29:10.512
shelved. But I'm working with our

482
00:29:11.712 --> 00:29:15.312
technology and licensing group within MD Anderson actually to try and bring that

483
00:29:15.352 --> 00:29:18.632
back and to be able to reinitiate a clinical trial.

484
00:29:18.652 --> 00:29:22.332
And that's actually work that we did here at the ACR

485
00:29:22.392 --> 00:29:25.952
meeting. This is a drug that's made it through the first three steps

486
00:29:26.452 --> 00:29:30.052
of Phase 2. I was actually the US senior investigator

487
00:29:30.872 --> 00:29:34.512
on this trial. We have not seen toxicity with this agent and are

488
00:29:34.522 --> 00:29:38.132
looking to move it forward to complete the Phase 1 clinical trial

489
00:29:38.492 --> 00:29:40.772
and to ultimately be able to test it.

490
00:29:41.272 --> 00:29:45.182
But in work that we've leveraged this, we've actually moved on from

491
00:29:45.212 --> 00:29:48.802
the work, and this was actually presented in December by

492
00:29:48.992 --> 00:29:52.832
Sanket Shah, who was a PhD

493
00:29:52.912 --> 00:29:56.292
student and then postdoc, working with Ari and with me.

494
00:29:56.742 --> 00:30:00.212
He actually presented this at the plenary session of ASH this December

495
00:30:01.032 --> 00:30:02.412
and showed that not only

496
00:30:03.332 --> 00:30:07.072
were the data that we originally found seen to

497
00:30:07.652 --> 00:30:11.592
show African ancestry was more commonly associated with these DNA

498
00:30:11.792 --> 00:30:15.522
damage sensing genes that we found in two additional cohorts,

499
00:30:15.572 --> 00:30:19.332
including a cohort from Malawi, that that was also true in other

500
00:30:19.372 --> 00:30:20.932
individuals of African ancestry.

501
00:30:21.812 --> 00:30:25.512
And he's since gone on, I won't go through all of the data here, but to

502
00:30:25.532 --> 00:30:29.072
describe that that's associated with a senescence-associated secretory

503
00:30:29.332 --> 00:30:33.012
phenotype that we've defined by multiplex protein

504
00:30:33.052 --> 00:30:36.852
imaging, by CODEX, and Lunaphor, and by

505
00:30:36.932 --> 00:30:39.902
additional immunohistochemistry and flow cytometry.

506
00:30:40.392 --> 00:30:44.192
And you can see that those individuals of African ancestry who were associated with

507
00:30:44.392 --> 00:30:47.972
SETD2 more commonly have an exhausted

508
00:30:48.512 --> 00:30:52.152
CD4 effector T-cell, a CD4 exhausted

509
00:30:52.232 --> 00:30:55.852
T-cell subtype, as well as a CD8 T-cell exhausted

510
00:30:56.512 --> 00:31:00.432
subtype. And that predisposes them to

511
00:31:00.472 --> 00:31:03.172
a biology that may be targetable in other ways.

512
00:31:04.112 --> 00:31:04.652
And so

513
00:31:06.452 --> 00:31:10.442
Sanket has gone on to validate that in multiple different

514
00:31:10.472 --> 00:31:14.372
ways. I won't go through all of these studies, but he's found that SAS signature

515
00:31:14.382 --> 00:31:18.132
phenotype in mice across our SETD2 mouse model

516
00:31:18.592 --> 00:31:21.542
and in human samples using RNA-seq proteomics,

517
00:31:21.912 --> 00:31:24.932
phosphoproteomics, and flow cytometry, as I

518
00:31:24.972 --> 00:31:28.876
mentioned.And so this new phenotype is one that we're starting

519
00:31:28.916 --> 00:31:32.576
to leverage in ways to be able to understand how this biology might

520
00:31:32.596 --> 00:31:36.496
differ for patients with diffuse large B-cell lymphoma.

521
00:31:36.926 --> 00:31:40.616
And this is just one of a multitude of different approaches that we've taken

522
00:31:41.036 --> 00:31:44.376
in a collaborative PO1 grant that Leandra Checchetti

523
00:31:44.836 --> 00:31:48.736
and I run between Cordell and MD Anderson, looking

524
00:31:48.776 --> 00:31:52.356
at projects in terms of the ways that epigenetics reprogram both the

525
00:31:52.396 --> 00:31:56.016
lymphoma and the lymphoma microenvironment, and lead to

526
00:31:56.516 --> 00:32:00.066
populations of patients that may be targetable in specific ways,

527
00:32:00.476 --> 00:32:03.776
similar to what I just described for the SETD2

528
00:32:04.496 --> 00:32:04.856
story.

529
00:32:06.276 --> 00:32:10.056
The other thing that we've done through this, in work that's been led by Michael

530
00:32:10.116 --> 00:32:13.756
Green, who leads our lymphoma group at MD

531
00:32:13.796 --> 00:32:17.236
Anderson, is taking this to single-cell sequencing of

532
00:32:17.456 --> 00:32:17.846
humans

533
00:32:18.816 --> 00:32:22.676
samples where he's helped to define lymphoma microenvironment

534
00:32:22.756 --> 00:32:26.476
archetypes or lymphomaps. And you can see here

535
00:32:26.556 --> 00:32:30.316
that across data that I won't go through it in much detail, but

536
00:32:30.536 --> 00:32:34.416
Michael has presented and published that there are three

537
00:32:34.496 --> 00:32:38.476
major lymphoma archetypes, one that looks like normal lymph nodes that we call

538
00:32:38.536 --> 00:32:41.906
the LN subtype, one that looks like fibroblasts and

539
00:32:41.956 --> 00:32:45.856
macrophages, or we call the FMAC subtype, and one that looks like exhausted

540
00:32:45.896 --> 00:32:49.556
T cells. And I think importantly, as we start to project these data

541
00:32:49.656 --> 00:32:53.556
onto clinical trials, that's helping us to define how we might move

542
00:32:53.566 --> 00:32:54.936
the path forward for patients.

543
00:32:55.936 --> 00:32:59.736
And I think this is really instructive in terms of the ways that these

544
00:32:59.796 --> 00:33:01.276
might provide value.

545
00:33:02.236 --> 00:33:06.016
So some of you may be familiar with this large randomized controlled

546
00:33:06.296 --> 00:33:09.796
trial that ultimately led to the approval of

547
00:33:10.056 --> 00:33:13.996
axicell in the second line, where with the ZUMA 7 trial,

548
00:33:14.076 --> 00:33:18.026
it took patients who had early relapse or refractory large B-cell

549
00:33:18.096 --> 00:33:22.046
lymphoma and randomized them to either receive CAR T with

550
00:33:22.096 --> 00:33:26.036
axicell or standard of care, which was additional chemotherapy and the

551
00:33:26.056 --> 00:33:27.866
potential of stem cell transplantation.

552
00:33:28.276 --> 00:33:31.146
And you could see that there was a large separation in the survival curves.

553
00:33:31.676 --> 00:33:35.615
Well, importantly, when you project the lymphomaps onto that, we can now

554
00:33:35.636 --> 00:33:38.856
define that there are patients with the lymph node architecture where there clearly

555
00:33:38.866 --> 00:33:42.656
are marked differences here for patients-- Sorry, the colors are

556
00:33:42.696 --> 00:33:46.636
flipped here, so axicell is shown in the blue and standard of care is shown

557
00:33:46.676 --> 00:33:50.456
in the yellow. That there are clear benefits

558
00:33:50.796 --> 00:33:54.436
to giving CAR T, both in that set, lesser benefits in the

559
00:33:54.476 --> 00:33:58.456
group that had the FMAC subtype, and really no benefit in the group that

560
00:33:58.516 --> 00:34:00.996
has the T-exhausted cell subtype.

561
00:34:01.496 --> 00:34:05.076
We're now taking this approach and projecting it onto frontline

562
00:34:05.476 --> 00:34:08.957
clinical trials, and you'll see data at ASCO

563
00:34:09.397 --> 00:34:12.566
for some of those frontline clinical trials that I mentioned that will get

564
00:34:12.596 --> 00:34:16.207
presented looking at this lymphomap subtyping and how that predicts for

565
00:34:16.276 --> 00:34:17.397
outcomes in those settings.

566
00:34:18.496 --> 00:34:21.576
I think Andrew Harpens, who I mentioned earlier, is presenting that as an oral

567
00:34:21.656 --> 00:34:25.596
session at ASCO. The next phase of that really is taking that to

568
00:34:25.676 --> 00:34:27.816
spatial, and I think one of the things that Michael has been

569
00:34:28.776 --> 00:34:32.016
very innovative in doing is taking the ways that we define

570
00:34:32.256 --> 00:34:33.375
subsets of

571
00:34:34.976 --> 00:34:37.236
both lymphoma cells and normal tissue cells,

572
00:34:38.076 --> 00:34:41.957
using single-cell transcriptomics and then projecting that

573
00:34:42.016 --> 00:34:45.676
onto spatial transcriptomics. And this is something that's really

574
00:34:45.716 --> 00:34:49.525
nicely leveraged the LEO cohort, where across the patients with diffuse

575
00:34:49.536 --> 00:34:53.457
large B-cell lymphoma, where we enrolled more than 2,200 patients

576
00:34:53.496 --> 00:34:56.316
with diffuse large B-cell lymphoma in the first five years.

577
00:34:56.357 --> 00:35:00.036
We had 454 of those that we were able to put onto a

578
00:35:00.076 --> 00:35:04.066
tissue microarray, and then to be able to leverage those

579
00:35:04.256 --> 00:35:07.976
patient samples to be able to do techniques like whole exome sequencing, spatial

580
00:35:07.996 --> 00:35:10.636
transcriptomics, and RNA-seq,

581
00:35:10.976 --> 00:35:14.876
that presented some of the data that I

582
00:35:14.936 --> 00:35:17.786
alluded to earlier. The other thing that's been very nice about

583
00:35:17.786 --> 00:35:21.576
this opportunity is that we also are able to

584
00:35:21.636 --> 00:35:25.116
see how the tissue samples that we have on TMA

585
00:35:25.156 --> 00:35:29.036
relate to the overall patient population of patients with diffuse

586
00:35:29.076 --> 00:35:32.736
large B-cell lymphoma. And so we can see whether there are systematic differences

587
00:35:32.776 --> 00:35:36.716
in those group, and we really actually did not see any by major demographic

588
00:35:36.756 --> 00:35:37.496
characteristics.

589
00:35:39.316 --> 00:35:43.056
And so I won't go through any of these data, but this is just a

590
00:35:43.096 --> 00:35:46.375
teaser to know that we have now completed the spatial transcriptomics on this.

591
00:35:46.815 --> 00:35:50.236
And these will be getting presented at a meeting near you.

592
00:35:50.916 --> 00:35:52.956
So what's next after this? Retirement.

593
00:35:53.276 --> 00:35:54.996
You're probably thinking retirement for me.

594
00:35:56.156 --> 00:35:58.696
But it's not retirement for me, it's retirement for CHOP.

595
00:35:59.116 --> 00:36:02.396
So CHOP actually is now 50 years old.

596
00:36:03.576 --> 00:36:07.276
CHOP was originally developed by

597
00:36:07.536 --> 00:36:08.096
a group at

598
00:36:08.916 --> 00:36:11.276
MD Anderson, including Eugene McKelvey.

599
00:36:11.376 --> 00:36:14.596
Actually, Eugene McKelvey's daughter worked for me

600
00:36:15.816 --> 00:36:19.376
a few years ago and has now moved on to another position at MD

601
00:36:19.396 --> 00:36:22.266
Anderson. She may be approaching retirement soon.

602
00:36:22.856 --> 00:36:25.496
And CHOP definitely needs to go there.

603
00:36:25.736 --> 00:36:29.376
But this is 1970s chemotherapy, and we really need to try and move

604
00:36:29.456 --> 00:36:31.696
beyond that to more innovative approaches.

605
00:36:32.376 --> 00:36:35.456
Jason Weston at our place has developed this SMART START regimen,

606
00:36:36.236 --> 00:36:37.836
where he took a regimen

607
00:36:38.676 --> 00:36:42.476
where patients initially got rituximab, ibrutinib, and

608
00:36:42.656 --> 00:36:45.996
lenalidomide as the first phase of this clinical trial with no

609
00:36:46.076 --> 00:36:49.676
chemotherapy, and chemotherapy was not added until cycle number

610
00:36:49.736 --> 00:36:53.586
three. This was published a few years ago in the "Journal of Clinical

611
00:36:53.656 --> 00:36:57.276
Oncology" with quite favorable progression-free survival curves.

612
00:36:57.676 --> 00:37:01.136
And when he first came out with this regimen, some people, including me,

613
00:37:01.636 --> 00:37:05.256
thought it was dangerous not to give people chemotherapy who had diffuse large

614
00:37:05.276 --> 00:37:08.236
B-cell lymphoma as an aggressive lymphoma.

615
00:37:08.266 --> 00:37:12.136
And you can now see that that was not only safe to do, where only one

616
00:37:12.236 --> 00:37:15.836
patient progressed on the RLI therapy, but that was a

617
00:37:15.916 --> 00:37:18.796
therapy that was well-tolerated and had very favorable

618
00:37:18.876 --> 00:37:22.798
outcomes.What he's done since then

619
00:37:23.288 --> 00:37:27.278
is actually moved on to a new regimen called ULTRA, so using a combination

620
00:37:27.308 --> 00:37:30.908
of rituximab, lenalidomide, acalabrutinib, and tafasitamab,

621
00:37:31.348 --> 00:37:35.318
where patients get four cycles of therapy, and if they get a complete response in

622
00:37:35.348 --> 00:37:38.578
the first cohort of patients, they only get two cycles of

623
00:37:38.588 --> 00:37:42.428
therapy. And in patients in the second cohort, which we've now moved

624
00:37:42.508 --> 00:37:46.268
on to and was presented at ASH this last year, patients get no

625
00:37:46.368 --> 00:37:49.648
chemotherapy at all. And I won't go through all these data.

626
00:37:49.708 --> 00:37:51.428
These have been presented previously.

627
00:37:52.128 --> 00:37:55.818
But what you can see for this whole trial of 61 patients, that we could actually

628
00:37:55.928 --> 00:37:59.808
take patients through a regimen without chemotherapy and have quite

629
00:37:59.828 --> 00:38:02.508
favorable progression-free survival approaches.

630
00:38:02.548 --> 00:38:05.468
And so we really need to rethink the ways that we're giving

631
00:38:06.228 --> 00:38:09.408
approaches for patients in the future with more targeted therapies,

632
00:38:10.108 --> 00:38:13.928
leveraging the molecular profiles, and more innovative strategies for

633
00:38:13.948 --> 00:38:17.708
giving treatment. And so our

634
00:38:17.748 --> 00:38:21.708
major future directions for our patients really are to start to

635
00:38:21.788 --> 00:38:25.548
leverage these SMART therapies. This is the next generation of our SMART

636
00:38:25.648 --> 00:38:29.518
trial, using gefitinib, polatuzumab, and gocatumab as

637
00:38:29.528 --> 00:38:30.588
the upfront therapy.

638
00:38:31.488 --> 00:38:35.228
And I won't go through any of the details here, but Dhai Jahar is leading this.

639
00:38:35.648 --> 00:38:39.548
This will move from being an MD Anderson-only clinical trial to being

640
00:38:39.588 --> 00:38:43.468
able to collaborate with outside institutions and are now looking for outside

641
00:38:43.548 --> 00:38:47.378
institutions, including those that I showed you earlier, to be part of that

642
00:38:47.408 --> 00:38:47.768
trial.

643
00:38:48.988 --> 00:38:52.918
And so in conclusion, really, I think there are a number of opportunities

644
00:38:53.008 --> 00:38:56.688
for reusing the molecular data that we have, both to derive

645
00:38:57.148 --> 00:39:00.978
surrogate endpoints, but also to define subsets where we can start to leverage that

646
00:39:00.988 --> 00:39:03.808
to drive new drug approvals, as I've shown.

647
00:39:04.768 --> 00:39:08.388
And then to be able to define optimal therapies with biologically

648
00:39:08.408 --> 00:39:09.508
defined scrub groups,

649
00:39:10.348 --> 00:39:13.968
and then using those to develop chemotherapy-free regimens that are

650
00:39:14.008 --> 00:39:17.568
emerging, and then hopefully through all that, to help

651
00:39:17.948 --> 00:39:19.848
CHOP to finally retire early.

652
00:39:20.788 --> 00:39:23.638
So with that, I'll thank you all for your attention and happy to take any

653
00:39:23.708 --> 00:39:24.108
questions.

654
00:39:38.668 --> 00:39:42.448
Hi there. Frank Slack from BIDMC. I'm not a

655
00:39:42.488 --> 00:39:45.488
physician, but I am interested in CHOP and

656
00:39:46.508 --> 00:39:49.928
retirement for it. I'm just wondering, in these SMART

657
00:39:51.008 --> 00:39:54.648
regimens that you're proposing, what's the effect on just complete blood count?

658
00:39:55.088 --> 00:39:56.988
Is it much safer?

659
00:39:58.448 --> 00:40:02.428
These have been regimens in general that have been much more easily tolerated, and

660
00:40:02.468 --> 00:40:05.988
there are selected patients where there actually have been some really

661
00:40:06.008 --> 00:40:09.728
unusual responses, both from the first trial and the second

662
00:40:09.788 --> 00:40:13.557
trial. There was actually a patient who got RLI in that first

663
00:40:13.557 --> 00:40:17.438
trial, got two cycles of therapy, and said, "I'm not getting chemo," walked

664
00:40:17.528 --> 00:40:18.868
away, and never came back.

665
00:40:19.768 --> 00:40:23.208
And we call him every now and then. He's still alive, still doing well, still

666
00:40:23.628 --> 00:40:25.148
doesn't have any evidence of lymphoma.

667
00:40:26.048 --> 00:40:29.868
We also have some patients in that second cohort of study who

668
00:40:30.268 --> 00:40:31.608
have gone all the way through the cohort.

669
00:40:31.648 --> 00:40:35.528
They still are not at quite as long a follow-up that don't have any

670
00:40:35.548 --> 00:40:37.948
evidence of disease. In both of those settings,

671
00:40:38.768 --> 00:40:42.588
the toxicity of the regimen was markedly less in terms of the

672
00:40:42.648 --> 00:40:44.808
cytopenias that we see with chemotherapy.

673
00:40:45.968 --> 00:40:47.948
None of those patients had hair loss associated

674
00:40:48.768 --> 00:40:52.708
with the regimen, and so they are less

675
00:40:52.718 --> 00:40:56.148
toxic in many of the traditional ways that chemotherapy is administered.

676
00:40:56.208 --> 00:40:58.548
Now, they're not non-toxic, though.

677
00:40:59.008 --> 00:41:02.588
There are toxicities associated with these regimens, like rash and

678
00:41:03.028 --> 00:41:06.368
other things that need to be managed, and you can get cytopenias with

679
00:41:06.428 --> 00:41:09.668
lenalidomide given particularly

680
00:41:10.528 --> 00:41:14.028
without attention to dose adjustment and those kinds of things.

681
00:41:14.068 --> 00:41:16.868
And so they do need to be carefully addressed.

682
00:41:16.968 --> 00:41:20.927
But with that, they've been much more tolerable than what we see with CHOP therapy.

683
00:41:21.768 --> 00:41:25.208
And I think one of the things we take for granted is that CHOP, in general, as

684
00:41:25.228 --> 00:41:27.768
chemotherapy goes, is reasonably well-tolerated.

685
00:41:28.268 --> 00:41:31.988
But I've had even a handful of my patients who have documented their

686
00:41:32.048 --> 00:41:35.988
course of CHOP therapy day by day, showing

687
00:41:36.028 --> 00:41:39.868
how they lost their hair, how they lost their appetite, how they were nauseous.

688
00:41:40.748 --> 00:41:44.528
And while it sounds reasonably tolerable for an

689
00:41:44.548 --> 00:41:47.088
oncologist, it's pretty miserable for the patient.

690
00:41:47.128 --> 00:41:50.888
And so I think we do need to think about ways that we can be able to modify this to

691
00:41:50.908 --> 00:41:52.388
be able to improve outcomes for patients.

692
00:41:58.748 --> 00:42:01.548
Hi, Chris. Thank you for the wonderful talk. I had a question.

693
00:42:02.668 --> 00:42:06.308
Because there's so much heterogeneity that we're describing in these aggressive

694
00:42:06.348 --> 00:42:09.868
lymphomas, do you have any suggestions on early clinical

695
00:42:09.908 --> 00:42:13.008
signal? Because there's going to be such a multitude of different modalities being

696
00:42:13.048 --> 00:42:16.788
tested, how do you generate the signal that actually gives you confidence to test

697
00:42:16.848 --> 00:42:19.368
those in later lines to actually get to patients?

698
00:42:19.948 --> 00:42:22.048
Yeah, that's a fantastic question.

699
00:42:22.728 --> 00:42:23.088
And

700
00:42:25.368 --> 00:42:28.268
my answer changed this week, I'll say.

701
00:42:28.828 --> 00:42:32.188
It changed in response to some new data that are hot off the presses that I

702
00:42:32.208 --> 00:42:36.188
mentioned from our spatial transcriptomics data, and changed in

703
00:42:36.248 --> 00:42:39.848
ways that we need to think about at least

704
00:42:39.908 --> 00:42:43.348
chemotherapy in the setting of diffuse large B-cell lymphoma and probably many

705
00:42:43.428 --> 00:42:47.308
other diseases. You probably heard in the plenary talk, the

706
00:42:47.348 --> 00:42:50.948
talk that Charles Shore's gave about plasticity across

707
00:42:50.968 --> 00:42:52.564
prostate cancer.Well,

708
00:42:53.704 --> 00:42:57.544
in our spatial transcriptomics data, we see tremendous plasticity across diffuse

709
00:42:57.584 --> 00:43:01.084
large B-cell lymphoma. So while we describe it as the

710
00:43:01.144 --> 00:43:05.044
ABC subtype or the GCB subtype, that doesn't really

711
00:43:05.084 --> 00:43:09.064
seem to be true. In ABC DLBCLs, there are lots of GCB

712
00:43:09.084 --> 00:43:13.044
cells that would mark phenotypically with a gene

713
00:43:13.084 --> 00:43:16.624
expression profile and are malignant and look just like GCB

714
00:43:17.444 --> 00:43:19.004
if you look at the single-cell level.

715
00:43:19.384 --> 00:43:22.984
And inside GCB DLBCLs, there are cells that look like ABC.

716
00:43:23.924 --> 00:43:27.744
And so it probably is not the traditional approach that we think

717
00:43:27.824 --> 00:43:31.124
about trying to give synergistic chemotherapy

718
00:43:31.704 --> 00:43:35.364
to kill the one lymphoma that is

719
00:43:35.404 --> 00:43:39.284
there. But it's the variety of lymphomas that are there and coming

